description.text:
3-D Snailshell Curve
Made by Jonathan Tarr, 3/13/2016
Made for George Mason University Math 493 - Mathematics Through 3-D Printing

This is a 3-D plot of a snailshell curve with the following variables:
aa = 0.6; bb = 2; cc = 0.1; dd = 6; ee = 2

This print takes 3 hours 15 minuets on a makerbot 2X printer (I only used the right side extruder but it is designed so that both could be used in theory) with a raft and supports. The dimensions in mm are ~102 x ~71 x ~59.
Warning: If you re-size it, you MUST re-lay it onto the build plate.

This object is a snailshell curve with parametrization of the curves that was designed and made using Mathematica and the following website for reference:
http://virtualmathmuseum.org/Surface/snailshell/snailshell.html

My apologies to everyone who has already downloaded this project for not posting this earlier, I was in a rush at the time. The STL file is different and those who downloaded it will notice it is much smaller. I also cannot figure out how to display the thingiview...

I printed this but forgot to upload a picture of the finished project, It came out very well, but the inside will be filled with support as it is hollow.

title: Raspberry Pi 3 Slim Case with Heatsink Cutout

description.text:
Slim case for the new Raspberry Pi 3! Case fits together with no mounting hardware.

Remix Improvements:

  • Added cutout for a CPU heatsink since RPi3s run a little hot. I used the following 13mm x 18mm heatsink -> http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00ZZ9P3QC
  • Tightened up a bunch of dimensions, camera & display ribbon cutouts shrunk so they're not so oversized
  • Added vent on case bottom directly below CPU. I used the following bumper feet -> http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B008DVSFNM
  • Increased case top and bottom faces from 1mm to 1.5mm to increase strength and reduce flex

I've uploaded two versions of both the case top and bottom so you can pick if you want display & camera cable cutouts or not, and if you want the vent cutouts on the bottom or not.

Enjoy!

bottom part "CaseBottom-_With_Vents" came out with 2.2mm poles, which fits nice into 2.75mm raspi mount-holes
holes in the top part "Case_Top-Heatsink_Camera__Display_Connector_Cutouts" came out as 2.9mm and are too loose to hold the 2.2mm poles
otherwise a really nice case

comments.text: Excellent design, printed mine straight from your files on a prusa, snapped it together and was off to the races, not sure why folks are having issues with it, i posted pics and my build settings.

comments.text: If you drop this in Tinkercad, and make the bottom piece 17.5mm tall, it will match up perfectly to the tops of the USB ports and Ethernet jack.  I also made the hole for the Heatsink just larger than the outside dimensions of a 50mm Sideblower fan output, and superglued the fan to the case.  My Pi3 is running very cool.  And with a Pi3, you can run the TWO LEAD (Only) fan wires to the 5v and ground pins on the Pi, and run it 100% of the time with zero noise... I mean it's completely silent, and I had to touch the fan to make sure it was spinning... You don't have control over fan speed, but the Pi3 definitely has the power to spin the fan at a decent speed, and keep itself cool all the time.

comments.text: I had the same issue using "CaseBottom-_With_Vents" and "Case_Top-Heatsink_Camera__Display_Connector_Cutouts" on the Pi 3. My posts came out to about 2.75mm, which is the size of the pi mounting holes, but I needed a bit more clearance for them to fit in the pi and the top part of the case where the holes were even smaller. I would move the vent on the bottom piece under the chip on the board and the GPIO cutout is too small if you were to attach a 40 pin header. description.text:
The Intex Pure Spa is a surprisingly inexpensive yet effective portable hot tub. After about a year of use, water started leaking from the pump/heater unit. A quick look inside uncovered the culprit - a black rubber hose between the pump and the heater had rotted and torn. It's not just hose though, it's got a flange on one end. Intex' web site only lists a complete pump assembly as a replacement part. Local hardware stores came up empty as did the local pool supply store.

IMPORTANT - This part won't work if it is printed out of hard plastic.

Ninjaflex to the rescue! Printed printed this with Ninjaflex flexible filament at 70% infill, it's a bit stiffer than the original, but with a hose clamp on one end and the attachments that fit on the flanged end, it flexes more than enough for a watertight seal and to dampen motor vibration transmitted to the heater.

description.text:
This is a filament holder. I designed it to have the least amount of parts. The printed parts are printed on a Felix 1.0 3d printer from www.felixprinters.com The goal was to mount it vertically on the aluminum frame of the printer, but the filament was intertwined so when rolling of it got stuck. For these kind of filament rolls, it is good to put it on a flat surface (floor, table). It is reliable and hasn't failed me yet after printing for lots of hours. Ingredients:
2 bearings (inner diameter: 8mm outer diameter: 22mm)
3x 250 mm M8 rods
1x 50 mm M8 rod or bolt
14x m8 bolts
3x printed parts

• Saw M8 rods to size according to description above
  • Print the parts from the included files
  • Mount the long rods onto the triangle shaped part with the bolts
  • Mount the bearings with the small rod and foot onto the triangular part
  • mount the filament placeholder parts
    • Note: It is recommended to let some space between the filament and the placeholder parts

The chunkiest model of the Trash-80 line! This is the hulky Model 4D of the TRS-80 family, which included a screen and two 5.25" disk drives. Scaled up it might make a good enclosure for a Raspi Zero.

Too lazy to print your own? Order one from http://store.rabbitengineering.com

How to build

  1. Print all parts in black, except for body.stl (which should be light grey or silver) and three copies of key_triplet.stl (which should be white).

  2. Print out stickers.pdf (on a old fashion, pre-millenium 2D printer) and stick the screen graphic onto body.stl

  3. Stick screen.stl over the screen decal

  4. Stick the keys onto body (following the photo for layout)

  5. Stick the two disk.stl parts onto the body.

  6. Stare lovingly at your creation.

description.text: You wouldn't run a single piston internal combustion engine without a counterweight as it would shake itself apart. This is the theory behind adding a counterweight to my y-axis and now I have finally put it into practice. First I lightened my y-axis carriage and build plate by drilling lots of holes. I then added a set of linear rails and a tray to hold two lead counterweights to offset the 1850 grams of moving mass that makes up my y-axis. Note the 6x20mm steel bar attached to the bottom of the counterweight tray which is mainly for rigidity. I increased the stepper motor size to 1.8A with a 4.8kg.cm holding torque to cope with the additional weight. So far I am very pleased with the results and I have got my sorbathane feet back on and it is no longer wobbling around like a jelly. First print came out beautifully but early days yet...

title: Adjustable Dual J Head X Hictop Carriage

description.text: This is an adjustable dual J-Head X Carriage for the Hictop Prusa I3. This will work for dual E3D style hotends with Bowden setups. I read one of the previous Dual X-Carriage design summaries and he mentioned he wished it was adjustable. So I took the idea and combined it with the slide from the Hictop Sensor mount this is a little bit of a derivative of. It is a really good adjustment system I've found. Extremely accurate. I currently only mounted one hotend simply because I don't know how yet to change those settings for the second extruder in the Hictop Marlin. The system worked well but after finding some of the things a little inconvenient I redesigned the slide. I moved the hotends as close as I could reasonably to each other and moved the mountpoint up 15 mm giving more vertical print space. The V2 is a great improvement I believe.

The only piece I printed with supports was the slider due to the fact that I printed all standing upright to help prevent any warping of the ABS. The version 2 I printed in high detail at .1 and printed it in my new favorite material PETG. This works extremely well. I printed all other settings the same. upright to make ease of printing. I always need to dress it up a little with a jeweler file so the slide is smooth. PETG is much harder than ABS so if you don't file it to a perfect fit it will stick.

Setup

Additional hardware required.
M3 x 16 Screws = 2 for X Belt
M3 nut = 11 for X Belt Screws, Slider attachment, Jhead Cap Attachment and slider adjustment.
M3 x 8 Screws = 4 total for Slider Attachment
M3 x 50 = 1 for adjustment screw
M3 x 25 = 4 for Jhead Cap attachment

Do one layer at a time starting with the Base Plate or you will not be able to get the next set of screws in place. Before placing the X-Plate set all nuts in their respective slots. You will not be able to place them after. Use super glue to permanently fix the thumbscrew top as well as the M3 nut on the adjustment screw so that it serves to keep the adjustment screw stationary. I strongly suggest filing the slider and slider base so that it slides smoothly but is still tight enough to prevent undesired movement. It is a very fine line. It also helps to pre-thread the adjustment screw prior to assembly. You will lose about 10 mm of height with this setup due to the longer extruder.

Six copies of this shape form a collapsed octahedron. Assembling the six pieces is coordinate motion puzzle as each piece interlocks with four others. Getting five together is easy (see 3rd image above), but getting the last in is a challenge (see 4th image)

So far I have only printed these on an Ultimaker. To get this to work, I printed the piece "upside down" on its point of rotational symmetry, and then added struts. Although the struts make the shape a little uneven once cut off, I haven't yet found a way to get prints in other orientations to work.  
I printed at 200% and with a raft to keep the struts attached to the unheated bed of my printer. Very occasionally the piece falls over when being printed (1 time in 25 copies so far). You could solve that with extra struts if you wanted. The fill was 20%.  
I included the OpenSCAD so you can remove the struts if you had access to another printing process.  
This item was inspired by a paper model of a collapsed octahedron that came from Martin Watson.

So I recently got my 3D printer and I came by some stuff on 3D printing waveforms so I thought I'd give it a shot. I decided to make an early Mothers Day present (just in case i forget).
The Waveform is of my voice saying "Happy Mothers Day Mom, I Love You".
I won't go into a whole lot of detail on how I did it since it isn't all too difficult but I'll do my best to sum it up.

So first I started out by recording my voice on my phone and emailing myself the audio.

I then opened up the audio clip in audacity and deleted the sections in between my words so that the Waveform wouldn't be too prone to breaking once printed. I also shrunk the wave so that the shapes were most defined, if you know what I mean.

After that I took a screenshot of the waveform and loaded it into GIMP.

On GIMP I used the magic wand to delete everything but the waveform and then messed around with some of the coloring tools to turn the waveform black.
I am not sure how exactly I did it since I'm not too familiar with GIMP. I just do not have Photoshop on my computer at the moment.

After finishing up on GIMP I saved the Waveform as a .PNG and I found this useful tool on the all mighty internet. http://image.online-convert.com/convert-to-svg
Just choose the PNG file you created and click convert.

Download the SVG file and go to this site: http://svg2stl.com/
Simply upload your SVG file and select the thickness you want.

Download your STL and load up your slicer or 3D printing software and Print.

Hope you enjoyed this very vague tutorial. All credit goes to the people who made those conversion sites. It makes this so much simpler.

This is a keychain for any swimmer.  It is the perfect size for any set of keys. The swim keychain was designed in Illustrator and printed on a CNC Lazer Printer. I made this keychain for my friend and I hope she is happy with it.

Instructions
  • Find a picture from google images, then copy and paste the image into a 3.5 inch. by 3.5 inch document in Illustrator.
  • Highlight the image and then click the Ojects tab, go to "live trace" then went to "make and convert to live paint".
  • Draw two elispe shaped oval with the "elispe tool".
  • Make the outside oval a vector cut (change stroke to .001 size).
  • Leave inside oval regular stroke size.
  • At one of the ends of the keychain add a circle for the key hole (highlight and make vector cut at .001).
  • Adjust overall size to desire of the size you want your keychain (highlight and click one of the arrows at the corner of the shape to adjust).
  • Now you are finished with your swim keychain!

This is a slotted cylindrical container that I use to hold Desiccant for my filament storage system. It is designed to fit in the spindle area of the filament spool.

I have made three sizes:

  • 19mm Diameter which should fit Taulman spools. (I've never tested it personally)
  • 30mm Diameter which fits my Hatchbox spools.
  • 50mm Diameter which fits my Orb Polymer spools.

The slots are 1.5mm wide so it should hold Desiccant spheres larger than that without spillage. I've noticed that broken desiccant spheres will still slip out, so as long as you haven't crushed your desiccant it should work.

The lid is press fit and the 3D printed layers kind of zipper together and hold the lid on tightly. I've added some finger nail slots to the lid so it is easier to remove.

On a side note I vacuum seal my filament spools in Waring 2-Gallon vacuum seal bags, part number WVS2GL. The bag size is 19.2 x 12.1 x 0.1 inches. I usually only do one spool but I can fit two of the standard size Hatchbox spools in each bag. I use the Waring Pro Pistol part number WPVS2000SA to vaccum seal the bags and it works really well. The gun and the bags can be found on Amazon.com.

Enjoy!

If you like the containers let me know, and if you use them for things other than desiccant post a picture!

Designed using Solidworks 2016

Update 01/12/2017: I have added a 19mm size to fit Taulman spools. I also increased the amount of material between slots to make it stronger.

description.text:
These are replacement joysticks for xbox 360 controllers. The design is suited for 3D printers and not identical to the original. I have experimented with a few different designs trying to find the more grippy design that is easily printed.

You need to purchase a t8 torx screwdriver( available at amazon or ebay) in order to use this. Disassembly is pretty straight forward and only require removal of 7 screws and a full replacement can be done within 5 minutes.

I was unsatisfied with the current joystick extenders as they spoil the joysticks and come off after a while so I have uploaded a seperate joystick with twice the length to be installed the same way, let me know if you need other lengths.

Please post makes if you enjoy the design :)

Update V2: added a bit more clearance to the bottom of the print for layer changes and sagging. It should print on all slicers properly now. Extended joystick extended from 8mm to 12mm ( original is 4mm)

Update V3: Increase tolerance for lower end printers, it should print properly on all machines now. Small ring along the edge for better grip added.
Added two experimental designs which doesnt work well enough, maybe someone can figure out how to make it more grippy.

EDIT: 16/07/17: Added source files from solidworks for easy customization. Feel free to customise the grips to your liking and post remixes if you do. The other configurations are avaliable in the configuration tab.

Resolution:

0.2mm or lower

Infill:

5%

Notes:

Rotate 90 degrees in the x axis so it is upright and print with supports.
I do not recommend going above 0.2mm layer height as supports will stick to the surface and be extremely hard to remove. Layers also break easily above 0.2mm.

You might need a raft if your printer or slicer is not calibrated properly. Feel free to mess with the print settings. Even at low infill settings it should be strong enough with 3 shells.

title: Endstop holder - micro switch to 8mm smooth rod

description.text:
My Mix G1 3D printer came with smaller endstop switches than what the replacement STL files had. Therefore, I made my own switch holder.  
This attaches a micro switch that's 14mm long with 7mm hole spacing to a 8mm rod (I have a smooth rod but I don't see why threaded won't work).  
I apologize in advance for the very bad job with FreeCAD, but the part works anyway as long as you don't try to change it ;)

• Attach the micro switch to the holder with two 2mm machine screws with the appropriate nuts. (You'll have to measure your switch to figure out the length of the screws.)

  • Clip the switch holder with switch to the rod.

  • Secure the switch holder to the rod with a #4 or 3mm machine screw + nut. The screw should be about 13mm long.
    • There is no countersinking, so button head screws work fine.

title: Needle Selector Combs for 5mm Knitting Machines

description.text:
Selector combs are used to move the needles on a knitting machine bed, in order to do certain patterns or stitches. A 1x1 comb is frequently used in casting on, and I made the 2x2 comb to make it easier to set up for 2x2 ribbing.
The points on each tooth fit into the needle grooves of the bed, making it easy to line things up.
These combs will work on any 5mm machine, which includes the White/Superba double bed machines. Eventually I want to make a script that lets you set the pitch, needle count, and pattern to automatically generate a cut file.
Cut out of 1/8 inch acrylic. Use to push needles around!

I had two problems with the default Graber i3 frame:
1 - The LCD cable was to short to embed it in the designed location
2 - I was tired to hear all fan noises when the print was in stand-by

So I developed a custom solution to hold the LCD above the electronic box and to manually switch between three functions (in my case the hotend fan, electric box fan and lights).

My printer is always bellow me when I'm standing, therefore this LCD position is quite comfortable and you can even rotate the display in the Z axis.
